My Dak Prescott take is that he's what would have happened to Tom Brady if he'd gone to a team shittier than the Patriots. Dak and Brady have some eerie similarities: both were late draft picks, both had quarterbacks taken before them, both play with a chip on their shoulders, both have shown instances of key decision making and clutch play.

The difference is that Brady went to a team with good ownership and a coaching environment that helped guide him when he was still young and vulnerable, and allowed him to develop into the GOAT he has become. I'm not saying Dak would have become the GOAT, but he definitely could have won an Owl by now if he were on a team with good ownership and good coaching, which would have allowed him to develop his positive traits and unlearn his negative ones.

Instead he's been stuck with Jerry and his parade of yes men and a generally incompetent management culture. So he's plateaued and I'm not sure he'll ever break free to a higher level.

>>127714169
If you're not that interested in minute to minute in game management, you can download skins with "instant result". Or you could set highlights to just "key" or "extended".

For faster load times between matches, unfortunately they didn't improve that until Fm22 when they finally had the game take advantage of multiple cpu cores.

Since fm20, you really can't go wrong with gegenpress or vertical tiki taka. Also, do note that the main tactics screen is your base defensive look. If it helps, try to emulate successful teams in real life. Try to pinpoint which positions you want moving forward, locking down in support, providing defensive cover. You can also use the website "ratemytactic" to play around and figure out how you want to play. Also, sometimes less instructions is more.

There's a little more to it than you may think:

- It's inspired by Brazil, as they had 80 D1 teams during the 1998 season. I really wanted to do something like that.

- There should be a lot more first division players being produced by Croatia, which should lead to better players and give me more people to pick up.

- I pretty much always win my division, so it's going to be interesting to see if the other groups come up with teams that can give me a challenge.

Nah, his point was that we are all "odd man outs" from each other. There's really big differences in culture (different foods, accents and slang, traditional and modern music, sports and traditions, festivities, etc.). We can understand each other using Spanish, but the cultural differences, I would say, between an Argie and a Mexican similar to (or perhaps greater even) than between an American and an Aussie.

There's different "cultural groups". We are definitively very similar to Uruguay, and Paraguay to an extent (Rioplatense culture). Then Bolivia and Peru form what you could call an Andean culture (mostly native influenced). Ecuador, Colombia and Venezuela form another cultural block. Mexico and Central America their own cultural block.

There was more British immigration and investment here than anywhere else in Latin America which explains why we are more into more typically British sports like polo, hockey and rugby, on top of football which is popular pretty much everywhere.

Argentina basically integrated into the British Empire economically (like a Spanish-speaking Australia) exporting beef and wheat, the British owned many businesses, factories and railroads, until Peron cut off those ties in the 1940s-1950s because the nationalists at the time saw it as a neocolonial situation. He bought the railroads from the British and shifted the focus away from exports and towards industrialization and inwards development.

Some say he ruined the country because he should have shifted towards exporting industrial goods to the USA as opposes to being so protectionist he hurt trade but that's another debate.

I work for a real estate asset manager here in Toronto. I'm on the public equity team (we buy stocks of real estate companies/REIT's) but most of the chads are on the private equity side (they buy individual buildings, usually apartments). They most generally come from upper class backgrounds and went to private elementary/high schools here in Ontario. UCC is the most prestigious/expensive of these. They play a lot of hockey, golf and squash (squash especially, surprisingly to me. I didn't realize the characterization in movies like Wall Street, Trading Places, etc was true. Squash is a big upper class sport). A lot of them go to the same high end gyms/social clubs in the city to network with other like minded young professionals.

I'm a bit autistic so I have a hard time getting to know people unless I work alongside them for some time. I only run into these guys mostly in the lunchroom or the odd occasion I need to work with them on something, so I always keep my demeanor strictly professional. I get the impression that despite them being great guys, we have nothing in common personally so it's hard to find commonality with them. >I'm aware they recently created a pan-South American professional competition, but I thought it was strange that it's only 1 team per country.
There will be two teams from Argentina for the 2023 season. Dogos (based in Cordoba) and Pampas (based in Buenos Aires).

I think Jaguares XV, was disbanded in favor of these two teams.

>Seems the better thing to do would be create a competition with maybe 6 or so Argentinian sides, and then one each from Uruguay and Chile, or something.
That's the ultimate goal, but there's resistance to disrupting the traditional amateur clubs, so they are building the professional teams on top of the amateur structure rather than replacing it. The idea being that good players can jump from clubs to the professional league, or directly join the professional league, but without disrupting the traditional system.

>What about a professional club competition with promotion-relegation open to Arg/Uru/Chil? Would that be realistic?
Not yet, but eventually yeah.

Rugbiers are nice people and Buenos Aires is relatively safe, I don't know why argies like to give our country here such a bad rep.

The only thing you need to use as a tourist in Buenos Aires, is common sense:
Don't walk through dangerous neighbourhoods at night, don't walk around with a huge-ass camera, and don't rent the city bikes you'll see around because only tourists use those.

Dress like you would back home, and you'll blend in. Use uber or taxis from your hotel. Or get the sube card to take the bus like a common argie. City centre and northern half of the city is safe, southern half stick to the touristy spots.

As for the rest of the country, Iguazu Falls are located in a touristy town, and Patagonia is very safe. Cordoba and Mendoza are like Buenos Aires and the same precautions apply.

>There is no reason why the US can't have good, fast trains in select regions except the terrible city planning
And this is a very common misconception.
The US has an insanely comprehensive rail network. More km of track overall by a massive margin than any other country. Even the tiniest towns had a train station at the turn of last century.
But when federal highways were built, and car ownership became the norm, and air travel began to be relatively affordable, people stopped buying train tickets because people who weren’t poor preferred cars for shorter distances and planes for longer ones, and people who were poor could pay less for a bus ticket between cities than a train ticket.
“High speed” rail would be a useless meme here, as you’d still have to drive to a station and pay for parking, or take a cab, same as you do for airports. And I don’t know about high speed rail prices in Europe, but I spend 10mos/year in Japan and can definitely say taking Shinkansen (bullet trains) are more expensive than a domestic air ticket between the same two cities most of the time.
The US rail network is still busy as fuck, but it is used for freight rather than passengers.
